}

3. One-to-Many and Many-to-One
........................
..............................

This is the relationship you'll use most. One Order has many OrderItems. Each OrderItem belongs to one
Order. In the database: the order_items table has an order_id column. The orders table has nothing
pointing at items

// MANY side- owns the relationship, holds the FK column
@Entity
public class OrderItem {
@Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
private String productName;
private int quantity;
@ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY) // always LAZY on @ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "order_id") // FK column in order_items table
private Order order;
}
// ONE side- inverse, uses mappedBy
@Entity
public class Order {
@Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
private String status;
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "order", cascade = CascadeType.PERSIST)
private List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();


4. mappedBy- The One Everyone Gets Wrong
......................................

// OWNING SIDE- @JoinColumn defines the FK column, manages the database
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "order_id")
private Order order; // field name: 'order'
// INVERSE SIDE- mappedBy says 'the order field on the other entity owns
this'
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "order") // 'order' must match the JAVA FIELD
NAME above
private List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();


