When to Replace @ManyToMany With Two @ManyToOne Relationships
The moment you need to store extra data on the relationship itself, @ManyToMany breaks down. When does a
student enroll? What grade did they receive? What is the enrollment status? That data belongs to the
relationship between Student and Course, not to either entity alone

// When you need extra data on the relationship- use an intermediate entity
@Entity
public class Enrollment {
@Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "student_id")
private Student student;
@ManyToOne
@JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
private Course course;
private LocalDate enrolledDate; // relationship-specific data
private String grade;


6. FetchType: EAGER vs LAZY
.......................
.....................
FetchType controls when related data gets loaded from the database.


FetchType                 When Loaded                                Default For
EAGER                     Immediately with parent-   always                @ManyToOne, @OneToOne
LAZY                       Only when you access the field           @OneToMany, @ManyToMany




7. Cascade Types
.........................
..............................

Cascade controls whether JPA operations on the parent automatically propagate to the related entities. Save,
delete, merge, refresh- each can be cascaded or not.
CascadeType What Propagates
PERSIST parent.save() cascades to children
REMOVE parent.delete() also deletes children
MERGE parent.merge() propagates to children
REFRESH parent.refresh() reloads children from DB
DETACH parent.detach() detaches children too
ALL All of the above. Convenient- but think before using



The two you'll use most:
CascadeType.PERSIST: Save the parent, children are saved too. You don't call save() on every child
separately.
CascadeType.ALL: Use when the child entity's entire lifecycle is tied to the parent. An OrderItem without an
Order makes no sense. UserProfile without a User has no meaning. All is appropriate for those


// PERSIST only- saving Order saves its items. Deleting Order does NOT delete
items.
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "order", cascade = CascadeType.PERSIST)
private List<OrderItem> items = new ArrayList<>();
// ALL- full lifecycle tied together. Profile lives and dies with User.
@OneToOne(cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
@JoinColumn(name = "profile_id")
private UserProfile profile;
// With PERSIST: save parent + children in one call
Order order = new Order();
order.addItem(new OrderItem("Laptop", 1)); // helper method sets both sides
order.addItem(new OrderItem("Mouse", 2));
orderRepository.save(order); // both items saved
automatically


8. The Infinite Loop Problem
.......................
........................

Fix 1:-

Annotation	                       Behavior
@JsonBackReference	Prevents recursion while maintaining parent-child relationship
@JsonIgnore	Completely ignores the field
@JsonManagedReference	Serializes the parent side


Real-Time Banking Example
Customer
@Entity
public class Customer {

    @Id
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "customer")
    @JsonManagedReference
    private List<Account> accounts;
}
Account
@Entity
public class Account {

    @Id
    private Long id;

    private Double balance;

    @ManyToOne
    @JsonBackReference
    private Customer customer;
}
JSON Output
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Sunil",
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": 1001,
      "balance": 50000
    }
  ]
}

No recursive customer-account-customer loop

Which side gets @JsonManagedReference?

The parent/forward side (e.g., Department → Employees).

Which side gets @JsonBackReference?

The child/back-reference side (e.g., Employee → Department).

